            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this HELOC calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This HELOC (Home Equity Line of Credit) calculator is designed
                to answer two key questions:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>How much can I borrow?</strong> – based on your home
                  value, current mortgage, and your lender’s maximum combined
                  loan-to-value (CLTV) ratio.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>What will my payments look like?</strong> –
                  interest-only during the draw period and principal &amp;
                  interest during the repayment period.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Estimating how much you can borrow</h3>
              <p>
                Most lenders cap your total mortgage + HELOC balance at a
                certain percentage of your home’s value, called the
                <strong>combined loan-to-value (CLTV)</strong> limit.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Step 1 – Available equity</p>
                <p>Available equity = Home value − Current mortgage balance</p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">
                  Step 2 – Maximum total debt allowed
                </p>
                <p>Max total debt = Home value × (CLTV limit ÷ 100)</p>
                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">
                  Step 3 – Maximum HELOC limit
                </p>
                <p>
                  Max HELOC limit = Max total debt − Current mortgage balance
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                If the result is negative, it means you’re already above the
                lender’s CLTV limit and may not qualify for a HELOC without
                paying down your existing mortgage or waiting for your home
                value to increase.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Interest-only payments during the draw period</h3>
              <p>
                During the draw period, many HELOCs require only interest
                payments on the amount you’ve borrowed. The calculator assumes a
                constant interest rate and an average utilization of your HELOC.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Average balance during draw</p>
                <p>
                  Average balance = Planned draw amount × (Utilization % ÷ 100)
                </p>

                <p class="mt-2 font-semibold mb-1">
                  Monthly interest-only payment
                </p>
                <p>
                  Monthly interest-only payment = Average balance × (APR ÷ 100)
                  ÷ 12
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                For example, if you plan to draw $50,000, expect to use 75% on
                average, and your rate is 8% APR:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Average balance = 50,000 × 0.75 = $37,500</li>
                <li>
                  Monthly interest-only payment ≈ 37,500 × 0.08 ÷ 12 ≈ $250
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Principal &amp; interest payments during repayment</h3>
              <p>
                When the draw period ends, your HELOC typically converts to a
                fully amortizing loan. The remaining balance is paid off over
                the repayment term with fixed monthly payments (if the rate
                doesn’t change).
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Standard loan payment formula</p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <em>P</em> = principal (remaining balance at end of draw)
                  </li>
                  <li><em>r</em> = monthly interest rate = APR ÷ 12 ÷ 100</li>
                  <li><em>n</em> = number of monthly payments = years × 12</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Monthly payment = \( P \times \dfrac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                In this calculator we approximate the remaining balance as your
                <strong>planned draw amount</strong> (you can adjust the draw
                amount or utilization to see different scenarios).
              </p>

              <h2>Understanding key HELOC terms</h2>

              <h3>Home equity</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Home equity</strong> is the difference between your
                home’s market value and what you owe on your mortgage(s). It’s
                the portion of your home you “own” outright.
              </p>

              <h3>Combined loan-to-value (CLTV)</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>CLTV</strong> measures your total mortgage debt (first
                mortgage + HELOC + any other liens) relative to your home’s
                value:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>CLTV = (Total mortgage debt ÷ Home value) × 100%</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Lenders use CLTV to limit risk. A lower CLTV generally means
                better approval odds and potentially better rates.
              </p>

              <h3>Draw period vs. repayment period</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Draw period</strong>: You can borrow, repay, and
                  re-borrow up to your limit. Payments are often interest-only.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Repayment period</strong>: The line is closed to new
                  borrowing. You must pay back principal plus interest over a
                  fixed term.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to use this HELOC calculator effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Start with “How much can I borrow?”</strong> – Enter
                  your home value, current mortgage balance, and adjust the CLTV
                  slider to match your lender’s policy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Switch to “Payment &amp; payoff”</strong> – Enter the
                  amount you actually plan to draw, your estimated rate, and
                  realistic draw/repayment periods.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stress-test your budget</strong> – Try higher rates
                  (e.g., +2%) and shorter repayment terms to see how your
                  payment could change.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes a constant interest rate (real HELOC rates are usually
                  variable).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Assumes a single draw amount rather than many small draws over
                  time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not include closing costs, annual fees, or early
                  termination fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not account for taxes or potential tax deductibility of
                  interest (consult a tax professional).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>
                This tool is for educational and planning purposes only and is
                not a loan offer or financial advice. Always confirm terms and
                payments with your lender before borrowing.
              </p>
